:::summary
Augustus Caesar (63 BC–AD 14), born Gaius Octavius and later called Octavian, was the first Roman Emperor and the founder of the Roman Principate. His long reign of more than 40 years established the *Pax Romana* — an era of relative peace, prosperity, and stability — and created the political unity of the Mediterranean world into which Jesus Christ was born.
:::

